      <!-- fever  -->
      <div data-aos="slide-right" data-aos-duration="2000">
        <h2>Fever</h2>
        <div class="symp">
          <h3>Symptoms</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>dehydration</li>
            <li>Headache</li>
            <li>loss of appetite</li>
            <li>Weakness</li>
            <li>sweating</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="prec">
          <h3>Precautions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              taking a regular bath or a sponge bath using lukewarm water
            </li>
            <li>
              making sure the room temperature where the person is resting is
              comfortable
            </li>
            <li>taking acetaminophen (Tylenol) or ibuprofen (Advil)</li>
            <li>drinking plenty of fluids</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- chickenpox  -->
      <div data-aos="slide-left" data-aos-duration="2000">
        <h2>Chickenpox</h2>
        <div class="symp">
          <h3>Symptoms</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>Feeling tired</li>
            <li>Fever</li>
            <li>
              A skin rash that is very itchy and looks like many small
              blisters.
            </li>
            <li>Spots that fade away.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="prec">
          <h3>Precautions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Press a cool, moist rag on the rash.</li>
            <li>Keep your child cool.</li>

            <li>
              Put a lotion with antihistamines on the rash. These lotions are
              available at the drugstore. If you don't know what to buy, ask
              the pharmacist for help.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- dengue  -->
      <div data-aos="slide-right" data-aos-duration="2000">
        <h2>Dengue</h2>
        <div class="symp">
          <h3>Symptoms</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>Sudden, high fever</li>
            <li>Severe Headache</li>
            <li>Pain behind the eyes</li>
            <li>
              Skin rash, which appears two to five days after the onset of
              fever
            </li>
            <li>Vomiting</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="prec">
          <h3>Precautions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Heavily scented soaps and perfumes may attract mosquitos.</li>
            <li>
              Try to avoid being outside at dawn, dusk, and early evening.
            </li>
            <li>
              Treat clothes, shoes, and camping gear with permethrin, or
              purchase clothes that have been pretreated.
            </li>
            <li>
              tructural barriers, such as screens or netting, can keep
              mosquitos out.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- cholera  -->
      <div data-aos="slide-left" data-aos-duration="2000">
        <h2>Cholera</h2>
        <div class="symp">
          <h3>Symptoms</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>Rapid heart rate</li>
            <li>Low blood pressure</li>
            <li>Thirst</li>
            <li>
              Loss of skin elasticity (the ability to return to original
              position quickly if pinched)
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="prec">
          <h3>Precautions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Avoid tap water, water fountains and ice cubes. This precaution
              applies to water you drink and water you use to wash dishes,
              prepare food and brush your teeth.
            </li>
            <li>Don't eat raw or undercooked seafood.</li>
            <li>
              Eat prepackaged foods. Or make sure other foods are freshly
              cooked and served hot.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
